New church ~ NASCAR Sunday a few weeks ago at @lacoliseum! It’s a tight quarter mile track so we couldn’t sit in pit and smell the burning rubber but the rumble roared all the way up to the roof top, at the 1923 Club. Watching the driver’s strategy is interesting on a tight track and for the first hour it was anyones race. There were a fair amount of crashes and resets. The first time I ever witnessed prayer in sports was during the two years I attended @marymountla highschool where our coach lead a #hailmaryprayer before the swim meets. Interestingly, NASCAR is the only sport that utilizes prayer before each race, asking for an extra hand of protection for their drivers, fans, and all those involved in the sport. Setting an powerful intention for saftey in a high impact sport is a good thing, irrelevant to one’s spiritual beliefs. Its not something I see often in life, and actually respect the commitment and tradition. I understand Nascar prayer is controversial, as a stunt woman and professional driver, having been put in dangerous circumstances, I would appreciate a positive intentional prayer. :) In the end, after more than 150 intense laps, @martintruex_jr won the cup, followed by @austindillon3, and @kbmteam. It was exciting full moon evening full of fireworks and the epic C-17 Boeing Globemaster flyover!
